Spread of SARS-CoV-2


World

The first case of SARS-CoV-2 was reported on 17th November 2019 in Wuhan, China.

By the 22nd January 2020 there was a total number of 557 cases reported worldwide (China - 548, Japan - 2, South Korea - 1, Taiwan - 1, Thailand - 1, United States - 2).

The map below starts on the 23rd January 20201 when 98 new cases were identified in China (95), Singapore (2) and Vietnam (1).

It shows the number of daily, weekly and monthly new cases since then. The line running along below the map indicates the trend.

Interact with the map:

  • Zoom in and out using the tools on the top right.

  • Look at the weekly and monthly data by clicking WEEK or MONTH on the top left.

  • Pause the timeline below the map and hover over the points for more info.

  • Move the vertical line on the timeline to see a specific date.



The graph below shows the number of new cases recorded per day per country.

Interact with the graph:

  • Choose a country using the drop-down menu. (Note: this panel is draggable.)

  • Hover over the graph to see the number of new cases recorded on a given day.

  • Use the tools on the top right to interact with the graph.



Sources

  • World SARS-CoV-2 data: Our World in Data

  • R code used: Code


United Kingdom

The first two cases in the UK were reported on 31st January 2020.

Interact with the graph:

  • Hover over the graph to see the number of new cases recorded on a given day.

  • Use the range selector below the graph to zoom into a specific period.


Sources

  • UK SARS-CoV-2 data: Our World in Data

  • R code used: Code


London

The first case in London (Lewisham) was reported on 11th February 2020.

The map below shows the occurrence of new cases in each borough since 24th February 20202. One dot equals one new case on the given day3.

Page last updated: 06/03/2021

  1. The number of new cases per country per day was not available in the dataset before the 23rd January 2020.↩

  2. There were no new cases reported in London between 12th February and 24th February 2020. Day to day variations in the data occurs due to a lag in the new cases being recorded on weekends and on holidays. There is a three day delay in the data being fully processed.↩

  3. Dots do not represent exact locations (e.g. address where the case was recorded) on the map.↩
